  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "When entering the US will I be detained for a bench warrant?",
  "response": "If you are attempting to enter the United States and there is an active bench warrant in your name, you could potentially be detained by U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) officers. A bench warrant is typically issued by a judge when an individual fails to appear in court or comply with a court order. Here's what could happen:\n\n1. **Screening Process**: When you arrive at a U.S. port of entry, CBP officers will screen your information against various law enforcement databases. If there is an active bench warrant, it may appear during this screening.\n\n2. **Detention**: If the bench warrant is confirmed, you could be detained by CBP until local law enforcement or the agency that issued the warrant can take custody of you.\n\n3. **Extradition or Resolution**: Depending on the nature of the warrant, you may be transferred to the jurisdiction where the warrant was issued. You could also be given an opportunity to resolve the warrant, such as posting bail or arranging to appear in court.\n\n4. **Entry Denial**: If the bench warrant is related to a serious offense, you may be denied entry into the U.S., especially if you are not a U.S. citizen.\n\n### What You Should Do:\n- **Check for Warrants**: Before traveling, it\u2019s advisable to check if there are any active warrants in your name. You can often do this by contacting the court where you believe the warrant may have been issued or by working with an attorney.\n- **Resolve the Warrant**: If you discover there is a bench warrant, take steps to resolve it before attempting to enter the U.S. This might involve appearing in court, paying fines, or addressing the underlying issue.\n- **Consult an Attorney**: If you\u2019re unsure about your legal status or how to resolve a warrant, consult with an attorney who specializes in criminal law or immigration law.\n\nEntering the U.S. with an active bench warrant can lead to complications, so it\u2019s best to address the issue proactively.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
